WEBVTT

00:00.674 --> 00:03.739
Thank you for downloading or streaming this message from Immanuel Church.

00:04.160 --> 00:08.648
We are one church with multiple locations, and we believe God wants to bless you right where you are.

00:08.688 --> 00:14.799
In a few moments, you're going to hear some practical teaching from God's Word that I believe will be inspiring and relevant to your life.

00:15.560 --> 00:25.458
First, though, if you haven't yet experienced Immanuel Live, we encourage you to go to our website, eclive.org, to check out our service times and locations so that you can experience Immanuel in person

00:25.538 --> 00:26.780
or through our online campus.

00:27.460 --> 00:36.232
If this message blesses you and you'd like to support the ministry financially, again, you can go to eclive.org and click on the giving tab and choose online campus at your campus.

00:36.912 --> 00:41.398
Thanks again for joining us today and we hope this message will be an encouragement to you on your spiritual journey.

00:43.300 --> 00:43.601
Oh, hi.

00:45.764 --> 00:46.484
I didn't see you there.

00:48.087 --> 00:51.571
You've joined us for another edition of the weekend service here at Emmanuel Church.

00:52.172 --> 00:54.034
Hi, my name's Cody Johnson.

00:54.626 --> 00:57.130
campus faster at the Emmanuel Church Greenwood campus.

00:57.651 --> 01:03.721
You might remember me for some of my work on the Savage Jesus talk, or perhaps that little ditty I did on complaining or jealousy.

01:04.141 --> 01:05.684
What a wild ride we've had together.

01:07.887 --> 01:11.152
Well, today, listen, I'm not going to be talking to you about any of those things.

01:11.192 --> 01:14.177
In fact, I'd like to ask you a question.

01:14.197 --> 01:17.202
What if I could offer you this tiny pill

01:17.762 --> 01:25.610
And in this pill, I could offer you a chance to decrease your anxiety, lower your depression, lower your blood pressure, and get rid of those pesky headaches.

01:25.950 --> 01:26.751
Would you be interested?

01:27.292 --> 01:28.173
Of course you would, listener.

01:28.533 --> 01:29.154
Of course you would.

01:29.875 --> 01:38.543
What if I could tell you this same pill could also improve your immune system, improve your heart health, improve your self-esteem, and increase your capacity for forgiveness?

01:38.924 --> 01:40.786
Would you want to take this magic bean?

01:41.346 --> 01:43.028
I'm sure that you wouldn't.

01:43.048 --> 01:44.850
Unfortunately for you, that doesn't work.

01:45.218 --> 01:50.286
And this pill is not going to give you any of those things, so I'm going to put it back in this tiny bowl on this tiny table.

01:51.988 --> 01:54.292
What we are going to do today, listeners, we're going to take a little trip.

01:54.592 --> 01:56.955
We're going to talk about the big G, and I don't mean Germany.

01:58.518 --> 02:02.464
We're going to be taking a little trip to gratitude town, and I hope that you'll join me.

02:03.846 --> 02:04.146
How was that?

02:04.166 --> 02:05.528
Was the cheese too much, a little bit too much?

02:06.710 --> 02:08.172
A lot of cheese on that, a lot of cheese.

02:08.232 --> 02:12.499
Wait, we are going to talk about gratitude today, so I'm glad that you've decided to join me.

02:12.799 --> 02:14.802
Let's throw that definition up there, shall we?

02:14.946 --> 02:21.617
So gratitude is the quality of being thankful, the readiness to show an appreciation for and to return kindness.

02:21.657 --> 02:22.578
I love the first part.

02:22.839 --> 02:28.708
I think we're all pretty familiar with that, the idea of being thankful, but that last part is something I really enjoy because it's an active state.

02:29.029 --> 02:32.334
I'm ready to return this kindness and I love that a lot.

02:32.855 --> 02:34.838
So what are the benefits of gratitude?

02:34.899 --> 02:38.144
Is everything that I said in that corny infomercial actually true?

02:38.184 --> 02:39.506
Well, actually it is.

02:39.682 --> 02:45.731
There are a ton of great benefits to gratitude, whether it is lowering your anxiety, decreasing the instances of depression.

02:46.012 --> 02:48.896
You can get rid of headaches through practicing gratitude.

02:48.916 --> 02:50.880
You can actually lower your blood pressure through it.

02:50.900 --> 02:52.101
Your immune system gets better.

02:52.121 --> 02:53.083
Your heart gets better.

02:53.464 --> 02:57.830
All of these unbelievable benefits and they're actually backed by research and they're backed by science.

02:58.231 --> 03:07.826
The Mayo Clinic has shown that if you do a daily gratitude practice, whatever it is, some people keep like a gratitude journal and they just write things down every day that they're thankful for.

03:07.970 --> 03:10.995
Or maybe it's through prayer, you express gratitude through prayer.

03:11.456 --> 03:16.284
Those have shown to have serious health and social and emotional benefits for your life.

03:16.304 --> 03:23.837
Harvard Medical School released a study where they tracked an experiment from two psychologists, one out in California and one down in Miami.

03:23.857 --> 03:29.647
And what they did is they got a group of people together and they divided them into three groups and they tracked something for 10 weeks.

03:29.667 --> 03:31.730
So what they did was they said, okay, group A.

03:31.810 --> 03:35.595
We want you to write down everything that you are thankful for for 10 weeks.

03:35.615 --> 03:36.637
Just write it down in the journal.

03:36.857 --> 03:37.658
We'll follow up with you.

03:37.999 --> 03:42.085
Group B, we want you to write down everything that irritates you, everything that annoys you.

03:42.125 --> 03:43.407
You write that for 10 weeks.

03:43.607 --> 03:44.208
We'll follow up.

03:44.448 --> 03:46.231
Now, group C, we just want you to exist.

03:46.311 --> 03:47.733
You write down everything that happens.

03:48.033 --> 03:49.055
Good, bad, or indifferent.

03:49.215 --> 03:50.757
We'll follow up with you in 10 weeks.

03:50.817 --> 03:51.037
Great.

03:51.318 --> 03:52.059
Awesome.

03:52.079 --> 03:57.106
And what they found was that after 10 weeks, the gratitude group was more optimistic.

03:57.218 --> 03:58.079
They were happier.

03:58.139 --> 03:59.121
They were healthier.

03:59.501 --> 04:01.003
And they went to the physician's office.

04:01.023 --> 04:02.786
They went to the doctor's office.

04:03.166 --> 04:10.457
Less times than groups B or C, all because they chose to express gratitude and make it part of their daily habit.

04:10.477 --> 04:12.640
Very fascinating stuff.

04:12.660 --> 04:16.265
And that's not just true in real life today or it's not just true in science or the medical field.

04:16.285 --> 04:18.468
It's also true when you look at the Bible as well.

04:18.588 --> 04:19.730
When you think about Paul,

04:19.970 --> 04:30.881
Paul, responsible for writing most of the New Testament, wrote a lot of letters in the New Testament, experienced this crazy, amazing conversion in his life when he realized who Jesus Christ was, and then he wanted to live for Jesus.

04:31.422 --> 04:42.934
And when he wrote a letter to the Thessalonians, he talked about his perspective on gratitude, but before we get to that, we gotta talk about some of the trials that he endured, because if you read through the Bible, he experienced probably more than just about anybody in the Bible.

04:43.414 --> 04:44.595
Here are some of my favorites.

04:44.996 --> 04:47.058
So he was in prison, he was thrown in jail,

04:47.746 --> 04:49.249
It says he faced death often.

04:49.469 --> 04:51.392
It's not enough that he faced death just once or twice.

04:51.412 --> 04:52.414
He did it all the time.

04:52.815 --> 04:54.738
He was beaten with rods publicly.

04:55.079 --> 04:57.102
He was stoned, not recreationally.

05:02.111 --> 05:09.363
And while he was imprisoned, he was abandoned by all of his family and his friends, and he was shipwrecked not once, not twice, but three times.

05:09.644 --> 05:11.026
How many of you have ever been shipwrecked?

05:11.138 --> 05:11.820
Of course you haven't.

05:11.840 --> 05:13.604
Technology doesn't allow us to get shipwrecked anymore.

05:13.865 --> 05:14.767
And we live in the Midwest.

05:14.787 --> 05:16.010
None of you have ships.

05:16.190 --> 05:17.834
So he was shipwrecked three times.

05:18.275 --> 05:24.210
So he endures all this and in his letter to the Thessalonians, this is his perspective and this is his attitude on gratitude.

05:25.026 --> 05:35.360
He says, be thankful in all circumstances, not just some, not just the good in all circumstances, for this is God's will for you who belong to Christ Jesus.

05:35.380 --> 05:38.384
And I think this is important to know in all circumstances.

05:38.424 --> 05:41.868
He's not saying be thankful for all circumstances.

05:42.449 --> 05:46.034
He's not thankful for the fact that he's in the public square and people are throwing rocks at his head.

05:46.178 --> 05:48.640
He's not thankful for the fact that people are beating him with sticks.

05:49.001 --> 05:57.509
He's not thankful that he's in prison, but in all those circumstances, because he knows who Jesus Christ is, he can be thankful because his eyes are focused on the right things.

05:58.670 --> 05:59.611
So that seems pretty simple.

05:59.651 --> 06:00.592
It seems pretty logical.

06:00.612 --> 06:01.513
This is something we should do.

06:01.553 --> 06:02.934
It's beneficial for our heart.

06:03.335 --> 06:05.016
It had an amazing effect on Paul's life.

06:05.056 --> 06:06.037
It's God's will for our life.

06:06.057 --> 06:08.340
So yeah, we should do this, but we don't do it.

06:08.800 --> 06:10.221
And why don't we do it?

06:10.242 --> 06:13.625
I think if you look at the human species, we're not very good at it.

06:13.645 --> 06:14.866
We're kind of lousy at it.

06:15.266 --> 06:16.328
when you really get down to it.

06:16.609 --> 06:17.851
But why are we so bad at this?

06:18.312 --> 06:21.899
I will tell you, it's your first feeling, because gratitude is hard.

06:23.822 --> 06:25.165
Gratitude is hard.

06:26.768 --> 06:28.592
It is not an easy thing to be grateful.

06:30.175 --> 06:32.319
But why is gratitude so hard for us?

06:32.900 --> 06:33.982
We're going to talk about that today.

06:34.563 --> 06:36.146
First reason is that we're rushed.

06:36.738 --> 06:37.719
We are rushed.

06:37.779 --> 06:42.464
We are so busy going from thing to thing event to event.

06:42.504 --> 06:50.311
If you've got kids, you're going from a practice to a game to a choir event to a band event to a production for Christmas time of Frozen, you're doing all these different things.

06:50.792 --> 06:52.373
Bouncing around, life is crazy.

06:52.393 --> 07:02.743
So you don't have time to stop and pause and be grateful for the blessings in your life because you are actually sprinting from blessing to blessing, not taking time to acknowledge the current blessings in your life because you're trying to get to the next blessing.

07:03.324 --> 07:05.746
We don't have time to be grateful because we are so rushed.

07:06.338 --> 07:08.941
Another thing that we do, and we are great at this, is that we compare.

07:09.501 --> 07:15.168
If we are lousy at being grateful, then we are Olympic gold medalists at comparison.

07:15.468 --> 07:16.329
We're so good at this.

07:17.030 --> 07:21.254
But when we compare, we don't do it in a way that elevates how we feel about ourselves.

07:21.274 --> 07:23.497
We always do it in a way that tears us down.

07:23.977 --> 07:25.659
We do it in a way that beats ourselves up.

07:26.100 --> 07:27.481
And we'll compare ourselves to anything.

07:27.501 --> 07:31.245
We'll do it in public, we'll do it in church, we'll do it on social media, we'll do it on Instagram.

07:31.305 --> 07:33.588
We'll do it absolutely anywhere.

07:33.608 --> 07:35.730
I'm guilty of this, and I've done some comparing today.

07:36.098 --> 07:37.781
I compare myself to other people all the time.

07:37.801 --> 07:41.847
I don't know if you've noticed this, but my beard is coming in a little bit longer right now.

07:41.907 --> 07:42.749
I'm pretty happy with it.

07:42.969 --> 07:43.971
It's got a little bit more body.

07:43.991 --> 07:44.952
It's in that soft stage.

07:44.972 --> 07:45.613
It's looking pretty good.

07:45.633 --> 07:47.336
It's not scratchy.

07:47.376 --> 07:47.997
It's not itchy.

07:48.378 --> 07:52.044
But I compare my beard to what other beards look like in the wild.

07:52.645 --> 07:53.486
I do this all the time.

07:54.407 --> 07:55.469
I do this right here at church.

07:55.509 --> 08:03.442
I don't know if some of you know this, but some of you guys here have really nice beards, and I hope that doesn't come across as strange or odd, because as I say it, it's really strange that I'm talking about this.

08:03.810 --> 08:05.473
But I do compare my beard to other beards.

08:05.493 --> 08:10.402
And the one thing I'm fixated on right now is the color, because I don't know if you've noticed this mine is kind of red.

08:10.763 --> 08:16.353
But when I look at other beards, like I see people with a little white or a little gray in their beard, and I think, man, that kind of looks good.

08:16.373 --> 08:17.255
I kind of like some of that.

08:18.357 --> 08:20.200
It'd be kind of nice to add a little salt to the cinnamon.

08:20.280 --> 08:20.681
That'd be good.

08:20.721 --> 08:24.608
Maybe add a little cream cheese to the pumpkin roll.

08:24.648 --> 08:25.490
I would dig that.

08:25.922 --> 08:26.683
That'd be really nice.

08:26.903 --> 08:30.707
And I can't be thankful for the fact that I have a beard that I can grow on.

08:30.767 --> 08:32.870
I've got family members that can't grow a beard at all.

08:33.130 --> 08:36.394
I can't be thankful for that because I'm comparing all the time.

08:37.475 --> 08:39.177
Another thing that we do is we don't get our way.

08:39.838 --> 08:42.601
And why would we be grateful for something if we don't get what we want?

08:43.862 --> 08:44.583
Goodness gracious.

08:45.404 --> 08:47.386
If it doesn't go your way, why would you be thankful for anything?

08:48.067 --> 08:49.028
And we do this all the time.

08:49.048 --> 08:50.770
You might have done this for Black Friday shopping.

08:51.106 --> 09:05.749
Because maybe you did some research, you got the family together, you're going out and you went to 57 inch, 4K smart TV, you found the best price point, you've been hunting for online, you know exactly where to go, but then when you get there, you can't get the 57 and sold out, so you have to settle for a 55 inch or a 50 inch.

09:06.390 --> 09:09.375
And then you have to watch TV like a wild animal, how are you supposed to live this way?

09:09.415 --> 09:17.067
You can't be thankful for the fact that you can afford a TV, you gotta be ungrateful and you have to be bitter because now I didn't get what I wanted.

09:17.728 --> 09:19.250
And maybe when you go out to eat,

09:19.394 --> 09:23.225
You're not the type of person who orders steak all the time, so when you do, you want it just your way.

09:23.627 --> 09:27.137
You want it medium rare, and maybe with little blue cheese crust on top of it, delicious.

09:27.598 --> 09:30.226
But when you order it and it comes, it's medium well.

09:30.434 --> 09:31.135
It's like a catcher's man.

09:31.155 --> 09:32.136
It's like you're eating a boot.

09:32.176 --> 09:32.897
This is terrible.

09:33.357 --> 09:34.979
And it didn't blow towards the blue cheese.

09:34.999 --> 09:37.282
Now it's just this moldy cheese on a piece of over-cooked meat.

09:37.322 --> 09:38.243
I can't be grateful for this.

09:38.443 --> 09:43.989
I'm going to let the server have it, not knowing that he or she, the person that's serving you, might just be trying to push their way through college.

09:44.190 --> 09:46.732
They're working a second or a third job, and they're just trying to do the best they can.

09:47.093 --> 09:49.335
Can't be grateful for them because it didn't go your way.

09:49.395 --> 09:50.437
Dog on it.

09:52.119 --> 09:53.000
And that happens sometimes.

09:54.681 --> 09:58.706
Another reason why it's so hard to be grateful is that we focus on the wrong things.

09:59.522 --> 10:01.044
Our focus is way off.

10:03.688 --> 10:08.315
When you think about this, this looks different for each of us, but think about how it might look in your life.

10:09.918 --> 10:14.324
So for example, in your marriage, are you focused on the fact that that person said yes to you?

10:15.045 --> 10:22.016
Are you grateful for the fact that you get to live with them and there's a person in your life that you can call your spouse and you love them, you adore them, and you care for them?

10:22.576 --> 10:24.860
Are you always picking apart the things that they don't do?

10:24.900 --> 10:28.946
Trying to mention their shortcomings areas that they fall short, are you doing that?

10:30.658 --> 10:35.245
When your kids play sports, are you focused on their coach in a positive way?

10:35.285 --> 10:37.028
Are you focused on their coach in a negative way?

10:37.449 --> 10:43.839
Are you thankful for the fact that they take time and energy to coach your kid through that particular sport and teach them about sportsmanship and integrity in the game?

10:44.280 --> 10:48.887
Are you focused on the ways that they're not giving you what you want and how they're falling short?

10:48.907 --> 10:50.029
Do you do that with the officials?

10:50.449 --> 10:51.631
Are you thankful that the official is there?

10:51.651 --> 10:54.315
Are you illustrating all of the shortcomings they have at their job?

10:54.536 --> 10:55.477
We're really good at that.

10:57.621 --> 10:58.482
Where's your focus at?

10:59.522 --> 11:00.664
And I want to share something with you.

11:00.704 --> 11:02.627
It's a story that's kind of personal to me.

11:02.647 --> 11:05.451
And I've actually never shared it publicly.

11:05.752 --> 11:07.174
So don't know how this is going to go.

11:07.214 --> 11:08.195
Hopefully it goes pretty well.

11:08.756 --> 11:17.029
When I told my wife I was going to share this story about my lack of focus and what a life without gratitude can look like and how it can harm you, she said, no, wait a minute.

11:17.089 --> 11:19.833
You didn't tell me this until we were married for five years.

11:19.853 --> 11:23.298
And now you're just going to randomly share it with the church and share it with the entire congregation.

11:23.318 --> 11:25.762
And I said, yes, I am so glad you understand.

11:25.982 --> 11:27.405
Thank you.

11:27.425 --> 11:28.306
Such a team player.

11:30.114 --> 11:36.343
So here goes, when I was, from the time I was about four years old to the time I was 21, I was a wrestler.

11:37.044 --> 11:41.050
And I don't mean wrestling in the sense like the term buckle and WrestleMania and the heavyweight title belt.

11:41.090 --> 11:44.214
I mean like high school wrestling, college wrestling, like that kind of thing.

11:44.995 --> 11:47.879
And it wasn't just that I wrestled, I absolutely loved it.

11:47.899 --> 11:50.163
Like it was my life in every sense of the word.

11:50.423 --> 11:52.466
And this is way, way, way before I knew Jesus.

11:53.090 --> 11:56.577
And so I gave everything I had to this and it was just something that I loved.

11:56.617 --> 11:57.800
It filled me up.

11:57.860 --> 11:58.702
It gave me confidence.

11:58.722 --> 11:59.684
I learned a lot about myself.

11:59.704 --> 12:01.207
I learned a lot about my life through wrestling.

12:02.129 --> 12:14.514
But when I was doing it, something happened and it went from being this thing that brought me joy and it went from being something that I like doing and it turned into something a little bit darker and a little bit more sinister because I got my identity wrapped up in it.

12:14.978 --> 12:17.761
I don't know if any of you have ever experienced that with something you're involved with.

12:17.781 --> 12:23.547
Maybe it's a hobby, maybe it was a sport for if you're a student, maybe it's your grades, maybe it's a job, your marriage or relationship.

12:23.927 --> 12:33.978
But the dangerous thing about this is when you get your identity wrapped up in something predicated on success or failure, then your success goes up and your self-confidence goes up and your value goes up and your self-worth goes up.

12:34.498 --> 12:41.205
But when you lose a game, you lose a tournament, you have a bad practice, the value, the worth and the confidence, they tank.

12:41.225 --> 12:42.066
And that happened to me.

12:42.818 --> 12:44.100
And it was that way for a long time.

12:44.120 --> 12:46.343
And I could never be grateful for anything with wrestling.

12:46.363 --> 12:48.106
I had to experience a lot of really cool things.

12:48.366 --> 12:49.688
I got to travel all over the place.

12:49.708 --> 12:59.043
I got to travel to Fargo, North Dakota, to Pika, Kansas, Greeley, Colorado, Waterloo, Iowa, Battle Creek, Michigan, Evanston, Illinois, Virginia, Beach, Virginia, all over the country.

12:59.383 --> 13:02.308
Just so I could wrestle and get the best competition, you could get.

13:02.468 --> 13:05.072
My parents shelled out a ton of money to do this.

13:05.152 --> 13:06.274
Was I grateful for any of that?

13:06.674 --> 13:06.835
No.

13:07.355 --> 13:09.559
I was never grateful because that was never the point.

13:09.579 --> 13:11.762
Internally, the point was domination.

13:12.258 --> 13:14.261
The point was to be the best you could possibly be.

13:14.301 --> 13:19.470
The point was when somebody walks out across the mat from me, my goal is to make you never want to do this again.

13:19.510 --> 13:21.794
That was the point, sole focus.

13:22.235 --> 13:23.437
It was never about gratitude.

13:24.619 --> 13:27.784
I was never thankful for the relationships I had with other wrestlers from other schools.

13:28.165 --> 13:34.376
I was never thankful for my brothers who kept showing up to be my practice partners, thumping after thumping after thumping and they just keep coming back.

13:34.656 --> 13:35.858
It was never thankful for any of that.

13:36.418 --> 13:43.186
I was never thankful for the fact I got to spend all this time with my parents on those trips because the sole focus and sole goal was a state title.

13:44.087 --> 13:44.968
The state championship.

13:45.008 --> 13:46.270
That was all I was building for.

13:46.610 --> 13:47.711
I was obsessed with it.

13:48.172 --> 13:48.853
I couldn't let it go.

13:48.893 --> 13:49.433
I couldn't sleep.

13:49.494 --> 13:53.038
I would stay up late in my night and I'd do stance and motion drills in my stereo up in my room.

13:53.058 --> 13:55.280
My parents would hit the wall and tell me to turn it down.

13:55.300 --> 13:58.124
I'd be doing push-ups until midnight one in the morning.

13:58.144 --> 14:00.386
It didn't matter because I was so obsessed with this thing.

14:00.647 --> 14:03.410
And I finally got my chance to do it, my senior year of high school.

14:03.682 --> 14:05.324
I get to the state finals match.

14:05.344 --> 14:07.467
It's me and this other dude, they drop the spotlight.

14:07.487 --> 14:08.729
It's at banker's life arena.

14:08.949 --> 14:09.770
They do the walkouts.

14:09.790 --> 14:10.531
They do the intro.

14:10.551 --> 14:11.252
They drop the lights.

14:11.292 --> 14:11.973
It's insane.

14:12.514 --> 14:13.615
It's all I've ever wanted.

14:14.216 --> 14:14.917
And I get there.

14:15.958 --> 14:18.301
I put my foot on the line and they blow the whistle.

14:18.582 --> 14:21.245
And six minutes later, I lose 12 to 10.

14:24.570 --> 14:30.738
What do you think happens to a guy that's got no faith in Jesus, no faith in anything?

14:30.818 --> 14:35.325
He's got his identity so wrapped up in this that he can't tell where the wins and losses end and he begins.

14:35.946 --> 14:37.428
What do you think happens to him internally?

14:38.229 --> 14:38.910
I was crushed.

14:40.112 --> 14:41.795
It felt like something in my brain broke.

14:43.157 --> 14:47.724
And I don't know if I was depressed, but I do know that I hated everything myself the most.

14:48.385 --> 14:51.570
I hated myself for a long time after that.

14:52.290 --> 14:54.433
because I couldn't make it make sense in my brain.

14:54.473 --> 14:56.315
I was so ungrateful for the journey.

14:56.335 --> 14:59.419
I had people come up to me and saying like, man, you made it like that's so amazing.

14:59.439 --> 15:00.920
I would have killed for an opportunity to do that.

15:01.201 --> 15:05.866
It didn't matter because to me it was a colossal failure on the biggest scale possible.

15:06.647 --> 15:11.053
I got called down in the athletic director's office about a week or two after because I want me to get sized up for the ring.

15:11.073 --> 15:13.916
Because you get a ring when you take first or second in the state and anything.

15:14.677 --> 15:16.640
And I'm getting my ring sized like, hey, what do you want to do with it?

15:16.660 --> 15:17.601
And I said, I don't want it.

15:18.302 --> 15:18.642
Keep it.

15:19.458 --> 15:22.522
Why don't you put it in the display case down here in the athletic hallway?

15:22.542 --> 15:23.583
Because I'm not taking it home.

15:23.864 --> 15:25.085
I want nothing to do with it.

15:25.967 --> 15:28.210
And the assistant athletic director said, you're going to want this someday.

15:28.230 --> 15:29.972
You're going to want to share this with your kids.

15:29.992 --> 15:33.457
It may not make sense now, but you're going to want this to, there's a keepsake.

15:33.477 --> 15:35.359
And I said, I want nothing to do with it.

15:35.640 --> 15:37.041
You figure it out.

15:37.061 --> 15:40.266
They'd descend at home with another student because they were worried I was going to throw it in the trash.

15:40.766 --> 15:41.828
How embarrassing is that?

15:42.288 --> 15:44.692
To conduct yourself that way, to be that ungrateful.

15:45.793 --> 15:46.514
And so I was.

15:47.138 --> 15:49.921
I couldn't even be grateful for the fact that I got to wrestling college.

15:50.421 --> 15:52.683
A small percentage of people get to play college sports.

15:52.723 --> 15:56.287
I should have been eternally grateful for the coaching staff, the facilities, my partners.

15:56.407 --> 15:57.488
Should have been grateful for all that.

15:57.508 --> 16:03.294
I was grateful for nothing because now it was all about replacing that void that had been left in my heart from that loss.

16:03.894 --> 16:05.216
That's all I could focus on.

16:05.236 --> 16:06.717
So now I got even more obsessed.

16:06.998 --> 16:07.998
I got even more absorbed.

16:08.019 --> 16:12.743
I was working harder, sacrificing more time with my family, my friends, my girlfriend at the time.

16:13.104 --> 16:15.666
Everything was on the back burner because this is all that I wanted.

16:16.482 --> 16:18.104
Then I get two and a half years into college.

16:18.124 --> 16:22.248
I look in the mirror and I hate myself more than ever because I'm not having the success that I want.

16:22.268 --> 16:23.389
I can't stand what I see.

16:24.750 --> 16:32.497
So over Christmas break, my junior year, I walk into my coach's office and 45 minutes before practice, I say the two words I've never set up to that point in my life.

16:32.958 --> 16:34.860
Two words I never thought would come out of my mouth.

16:36.021 --> 16:36.361
I quit.

16:41.346 --> 16:42.847
Here's the best part.

16:42.867 --> 16:44.269
I get nobody else to blame on myself.

16:45.089 --> 16:45.810
It was all my fault.

16:46.370 --> 16:49.854
100% take accountability and ownership for all of it.

16:49.874 --> 16:53.199
Because I could have been grateful for everything up to that point.

16:53.219 --> 16:56.703
But here's the thing I learned about living a life without gratitude at 21 years of age.

16:57.244 --> 17:02.490
If you live a life without gratitude, you can push the thing that you love most right out of your life.

17:04.773 --> 17:06.476
That is 100% certain.

17:06.556 --> 17:07.216
That can happen.

17:09.760 --> 17:11.602
And I share this as a cautionary tale.

17:11.810 --> 17:17.119
But I also share this as a guy that got this wrong and I want you to hear this more clearly than anything I say to you today.

17:17.480 --> 17:18.903
I don't want this for you.

17:20.686 --> 17:25.514
I can't tell you how badly I messed that up and I don't want that for your life.

17:25.995 --> 17:29.281
I do not want you to live a life without gratitude because it will mess you up.

17:29.642 --> 17:34.791
Instead, what I want is you to take Paul's approach and I want you to be thankful and grateful in all circumstances.

17:34.931 --> 17:36.594
That is what I want for you.

17:37.314 --> 17:43.730
So now that we know what this looks like when it goes south and when it goes bad, now that we know how important it is to be grateful, what are we going to do about it?

17:44.231 --> 17:46.577
How are we going to be grateful in all circumstances?

17:47.379 --> 17:47.820
I'll tell you how.

17:47.860 --> 17:50.386
The first thing we're going to do is we're going to pause.

18:06.754 --> 18:07.776
It's 15 seconds.

18:07.976 --> 18:08.317
Oh, man.

18:09.098 --> 18:10.581
Some of you are like, get to the next word, man.

18:10.601 --> 18:11.502
Come on, look, we got to go.

18:12.384 --> 18:15.148
It's so hard to pause, but we have to pause.

18:15.669 --> 18:16.531
We've got to pause.

18:16.551 --> 18:18.654
It's so important for restoration.

18:18.695 --> 18:19.957
It's so important for recovery.

18:19.977 --> 18:22.060
It's so important for spiritual rejuvenation.

18:22.080 --> 18:27.630
It's so important to pause so that we can actually take time to remember who Jesus Christ is and what He has done for us.

18:27.650 --> 18:32.338
Is Him, is mixed martial arts, Jorge Masvidal would say, it is super necessary to pause.

18:32.674 --> 18:34.879
We've got to pause and we've got to get this right.

18:35.259 --> 18:37.604
When I think about this, pause is a way to reflect and restore.

18:37.865 --> 18:39.849
The one thing I think of is the movie Tombstone.

18:39.869 --> 18:41.853
How many of you have seen the movie Tombstone here?

18:42.494 --> 18:43.456
Yeah, that's what I'm talking about.

18:43.476 --> 18:43.817
There we go.

18:44.218 --> 18:45.160
So that's my favorite movie.

18:45.180 --> 18:45.681
It's a western.

18:45.701 --> 18:47.284
It was made in like the early to mid 90s.

18:47.705 --> 18:50.511
Doc Holiday, Val Kilmer, Wyatt Earp.

18:50.531 --> 18:52.114
It gets a great, great story.

18:52.290 --> 19:03.507
But when Doc Holiday, excuse me, when Wyatt Earp and his brothers Morgan and Virgil are getting off the train in Tombstone, they're with their wives and they're all standing together and they're all taking a moment just to be appreciative of that time that they're together as a family.

19:03.808 --> 19:06.832
And they stop in front of this mirror and they're just kind of taking it all in.

19:07.914 --> 19:11.800
And Morgan, the youngest brother, he comes up and he starts to say something Wyatt cuts him off.

19:11.820 --> 19:13.923
He's like, no, no, no, don't talk, just, yeah.

19:15.506 --> 19:21.074
And they take that moment in, they reflect and they take that moment to acknowledge how grateful they are to be together as a family.

19:21.666 --> 19:25.010
And I thought that was so cool, and that's something that I always think of.

19:25.030 --> 19:26.432
You can even find this in Genesis.

19:26.632 --> 19:28.615
In Genesis chapter two, verses two and three.

19:28.635 --> 19:31.138
I want you to check this out, this idea of pausing.

19:32.780 --> 19:35.904
On the seventh day, God had finished his work of creation.

19:36.224 --> 19:37.666
That's a lot of work to knock out in six days.

19:38.287 --> 19:39.188
I feel like we're undermining that.

19:39.208 --> 19:39.669
What did you do?

19:40.029 --> 19:40.369
Everything.

19:42.172 --> 19:42.532
All of it.

19:42.552 --> 19:43.013
Six days.

19:43.133 --> 19:43.453
All of it.

19:43.473 --> 19:43.694
Done.

19:43.814 --> 19:43.954
Yup.

19:44.054 --> 19:45.336
Get all of it.

19:45.356 --> 19:46.757
They just kind of casually throw it in there.

19:46.777 --> 19:47.218
I love that.

19:48.130 --> 19:51.594
So he finished his work of creation and then he rested from all his work.

19:51.895 --> 19:54.598
Like we highlight that in yellow because I can't emphasize that enough.

19:54.998 --> 19:55.639
All of the work.

19:56.240 --> 19:56.560
All of it.

19:57.241 --> 19:58.042
Every single thing.

19:58.082 --> 19:58.583
All of it.

20:00.085 --> 20:06.433
And God bless the seventh day and he declared it holy because it was the day when he rested again from all his work of creation.

20:06.913 --> 20:09.016
God answered not one email on that day.

20:09.036 --> 20:10.898
Nothing.

20:11.650 --> 20:19.538
He didn't make any deals like we do as Americans, like we take time, like, you know what, I'll take the day off, I'll make this day my Sabbath day, but I'm gonna answer like 10 emails.

20:19.558 --> 20:22.641
Or I'll take this day my Sabbath day, I'm only gonna go into work for a little bit.

20:22.901 --> 20:26.405
Or I'll take this day as my Sabbath day and I'll play with my kids after I do this thing.

20:26.625 --> 20:27.225
No, no, no, no, no.

20:27.706 --> 20:34.272
He took a break from all of it, because even God was self-aware to know that he can't go 100 miles an hour, seven days a week.

20:34.833 --> 20:40.018
But we think that we can, because we know better and we try to outwork God, don't we?

20:40.514 --> 20:41.235
We do that all the time.

20:41.295 --> 20:42.276
No, no, no, I'll rest later.

20:42.296 --> 20:43.118
It's not a big deal.

20:43.458 --> 20:43.618
No.

20:44.379 --> 20:45.601
And we wonder why we're anxious.

20:45.621 --> 20:46.642
We wonder why we're tired.

20:46.683 --> 20:47.804
We wonder why we're stressed out.

20:47.844 --> 20:51.429
It's because we are working at a pace that is seemingly trying to surpass God.

20:52.531 --> 20:55.094
So when you're tired and you're sick, you're like, man, I don't know what's going on.

20:55.695 --> 20:56.997
Don't try not to outwork God anymore.

20:57.538 --> 21:00.522
Get some rest, make that day holy, receive it as Sabbath.

21:00.942 --> 21:02.885
Eugene Peterson talks about it this way and it's great.

21:03.326 --> 21:06.370
He says, Sabbath is the time set aside to do nothing.

21:06.430 --> 21:07.151
Nothing.

21:08.052 --> 21:09.394
So that we can receive everything.

21:09.794 --> 21:18.447
To set aside our anxious attempts to make ourselves useful, to set aside our tense restlessness, to set aside our media-saturated boredom.

21:19.488 --> 21:24.276
Sabbath, arrest, is the time to receive silence and let it deepen into gratitude.

21:24.917 --> 21:26.199
Man, this is your time with God.

21:26.279 --> 21:27.360
Don't rush through it.

21:27.941 --> 21:32.448
That silence, that gap, we talk about it in the Un hurried series a few weeks back.

21:32.828 --> 21:36.594
You can go back and check that out on the podcast or YouTube, creating that margin.

21:36.674 --> 21:41.479
You create that margin so you can get that time to be with God and let it deepen into gratitude.

21:41.539 --> 21:42.500
That's the point of it.

21:42.760 --> 21:43.861
Don't rush through that.

21:44.582 --> 21:45.343
Do not rush through that.

21:45.363 --> 21:46.263
You gotta make a decision.

21:46.283 --> 21:49.587
You might have to say no to people and that's all good because it matters that much.

21:49.987 --> 21:51.208
You gotta make that decision.

21:51.929 --> 21:54.852
We also have to decide that I don't have to get my way.

21:56.133 --> 21:57.675
That's a big decision we gotta make.

21:57.715 --> 22:00.678
I gotta decide that I don't have to get my way.

22:02.279 --> 22:05.202
You go back to Paul in the letter he wrote to the Philippians when he's

22:05.442 --> 22:09.166
He's actually on house arrest and he's writing a letter to thank people for giving him some money.

22:09.647 --> 22:11.108
And in Philippians, he says this.

22:11.148 --> 22:13.010
He says, don't be selfish.

22:13.811 --> 22:14.933
Don't try to impress others.

22:14.993 --> 22:15.593
Be humble.

22:16.374 --> 22:18.316
Thinking of others is better than yourselves.

22:19.778 --> 22:23.342
Don't look out for only your own interests, but take an interest in others too.

22:24.163 --> 22:28.688
This idea of being humble is all about putting people ahead of yourself.

22:28.708 --> 22:30.450
It's all about putting other people first.

22:30.882 --> 22:36.209
Pastor Danny talks about it sometimes, especially in the confines of a marriage, preferring the other person, preferring the spouse.

22:36.229 --> 22:38.132
You need to prefer other people.

22:38.873 --> 22:39.794
This is very important.

22:40.755 --> 22:42.057
And you can do this in a lot of different ways.

22:42.077 --> 22:43.259
It doesn't need to be a big way.

22:43.279 --> 22:48.305
So say if you're in a relationship, you're in a marriage instead of getting your own way all the time and trying to watch a football game.

22:48.345 --> 22:50.068
Maybe it's looking over at your wife and saying, you know what?

22:51.289 --> 22:52.771
Why don't we watch Pioneer Woman tonight?

22:52.791 --> 22:53.432
Why don't we do that?

22:55.074 --> 22:57.237
Why don't we see how she makes a southern quiche?

22:57.618 --> 22:58.078
Why don't we do that?

22:58.479 --> 22:59.981
Oh man, she put two sticks of butter in it.

23:00.021 --> 23:00.882
Baby, that's awesome.

23:01.090 --> 23:01.531
That's cool.

23:02.612 --> 23:16.292
You know, maybe you do something like that or maybe when you're going out to eat instead of rushing in the door and like slamming the door on the people behind you that are also coming in to grab a meal, maybe you hold the door open for them and you let them go in first so they can put their name in and they can eat before you do.

23:16.312 --> 23:17.214
I know that's tough.

23:17.674 --> 23:23.363
I'm guilty of that sometimes too, but those are just a couple of different ways you can put people first and humble yourselves.

23:23.383 --> 23:24.244
Let me ask you a question.

23:24.284 --> 23:25.566
When is the last time that you did this?

23:25.606 --> 23:28.370
When is the last time that you put somebody before yourself?

23:31.330 --> 23:33.273
It's a hard thing to think about.

23:33.293 --> 23:37.599
Maybe some of you are really good at it, but if you're not, so good at it, maybe this is a good time for a heart check.

23:38.400 --> 23:39.281
It's a good time of year to do it.

23:39.301 --> 23:40.603
And in the book, the ego is the enemy.

23:41.044 --> 23:42.566
Ryan Holiday talks about humility.

23:42.586 --> 23:46.632
He says, when we remove ego, we're left with what is real.

23:46.652 --> 23:48.375
What replaces ego is humility.

23:48.435 --> 23:51.399
Yes, but rock hard humility and confidence.

23:52.000 --> 23:55.265
And that confidence comes from knowing what you need to do and how you need to live.

23:55.845 --> 23:57.327
Because we're not called to put ourselves first.

23:57.348 --> 23:59.090
We're called to put others before us.

23:59.682 --> 24:01.143
That's the same model that Jesus said.

24:01.223 --> 24:05.527
How humble was Jesus to come down here and do what he did for us?

24:06.028 --> 24:08.610
Even just to come down and live as a human being.

24:08.690 --> 24:09.331
He was God.

24:09.351 --> 24:22.043
He had all the power available to him and you in the universe, but instead he comes down here, is born as an infant, grows into a man, subjects himself to being mocked and beaten, all these different things, because he wanted to serve.

24:23.324 --> 24:24.745
It's the perfect model to follow.

24:25.686 --> 24:27.048
It's just a shift in perspective.

24:27.228 --> 24:28.409
It's a different way to think about things.

24:28.449 --> 24:29.650
It's a different way to focus.

24:30.466 --> 24:35.553
The last thing you need to do, this might be one of the most important is we need to focus on what we have.

24:37.115 --> 24:38.356
Got to focus on what we have.

24:40.760 --> 24:44.204
I love what Brene Brown says about this, this idea of focus.

24:45.025 --> 24:48.229
I don't have to chase extraordinary moments to find happiness.

24:48.990 --> 24:50.032
We had caught up in that idea.

24:50.072 --> 24:54.738
We think that these extraordinary moments are the only cause for gratitude, the only cause for us to be thankful.

24:55.074 --> 24:57.056
like that big first birthday party for the kids.

24:57.076 --> 24:58.237
It's got to be the biggest thing in the world.

24:58.317 --> 24:59.278
We can be thankful for that.

24:59.538 --> 25:01.480
We can only be thankful around Thanksgiving or Christmas.

25:01.520 --> 25:04.723
It's not true because it's right in front of me.

25:05.624 --> 25:09.788
If I'm paying attention and if I'm practicing gratitude, it's all right there.

25:11.410 --> 25:14.493
And a lot of times we forget about the thing that's the easiest thing to be grateful for.

25:15.073 --> 25:18.617
It's our relationship with Jesus Christ and who He is and what He's done for us.

25:19.558 --> 25:24.242
Let me forget that one all the time because we're rushed, because we're trying to get our way.

25:24.706 --> 25:26.268
and our focus is off just a little bit.

25:27.169 --> 25:34.198
And I want to go back to that letter that Paul was writing in Philippians, because he's got a really interesting perspective, but I want you to think about it in a little bit different way.

25:34.298 --> 25:37.382
It's verses 11 through 13, chapter four.

25:37.923 --> 25:43.489
It says, I have learned how to be content with whatever I have.

25:44.190 --> 25:46.974
I know how to live on almost nothing or with everything.

25:48.055 --> 25:53.522
I have learned that the secret of living in every situation, whether it is with a full stomach or empty, with plenty or little.

25:54.562 --> 25:57.626
For I can do everything through Christ who gives me strength.

25:57.646 --> 25:59.989
I wanna hang out here for a second.

26:00.029 --> 26:02.833
This one, this verse gets a lot of publicity, this gets a lot of press.

26:03.354 --> 26:12.827
And I wanna say this to you, if this is your anchor verse, this is your life first that you use to get you out of bed in the morning because you're racked with anxiety or depression, this gets you through the day, keep it.

26:13.708 --> 26:21.138
If you've just lost somebody and this is the verse that gives you strength to push on and find support and to take solace in Jesus Christ, keep it.

26:21.858 --> 26:31.952
But what I want you to do is to take the two verses before it and use it to strengthen it for you and to strengthen your understanding and make it a little bit more personal because this is all about finding contentment in Jesus Christ.

26:32.873 --> 26:51.218
Yes, it's good to be thankful for the blessings and the gifts in our lives, but to have that ultimate contentment and to focus all of our gratitude and all that energy on Jesus Christ, man, that's gonna open up so many doors for you and you're gonna experience a freedom unlike anything you've ever felt before when it comes to your heart, when it comes to your soul, when it comes to being truly grateful.

26:52.354 --> 26:54.316
And I can tell you that I've had experience with that in my life.

26:54.376 --> 26:59.422
I told you a little bit about my experience with wrestling, but the cool thing about it is God didn't leave the story there.

27:00.162 --> 27:16.340
And I'm so thankful for that because once I accepted Christ and once I stepped into that relationship in 2011, five years after I had lost in that state title match, when my focus was crystal clear and my love and my adoration and my gratitude was so focused on Jesus, man, it changed my life forever.

27:17.221 --> 27:22.226
And it was almost like I was able to see wrestling and that thing I loved through his perspective instead of my own.

27:22.658 --> 27:25.243
Because now he was my source of perfection.

27:26.204 --> 27:27.847
He was my only source of victory.

27:28.709 --> 27:32.876
He's the only thing that I needed to put stock in when it comes to my self-worth and confidence.

27:32.896 --> 27:33.818
He's my everything.

27:34.559 --> 27:38.807
And once he's my everything, now I'm just free to enjoy wrestling for what it is.

27:39.328 --> 27:40.170
And it changed my life.

27:40.450 --> 27:47.122
I actually got to coach on two different high school teams after I trusted in Christ because my head was in the right place.

27:47.266 --> 27:50.270
And now when young men and young women will come off the mat, win or lose.

27:50.290 --> 27:51.752
Yeah, we're going to talk about being physical.

27:51.912 --> 27:52.973
We're going to talk about being intense.

27:52.993 --> 27:54.335
We're going to talk about having great technique.

27:54.595 --> 27:55.556
All those things are important.

27:55.897 --> 27:58.720
But win or lose, when you come off the mat, you're still valued.

27:58.740 --> 27:59.501
You're still loved.

28:00.262 --> 28:01.524
You're still a unique human being.

28:01.584 --> 28:02.485
You're still awesome.

28:03.066 --> 28:03.586
It's all good.

28:03.686 --> 28:04.187
Win or lose.

28:04.207 --> 28:05.729
That's not the most important thing in the world.

28:06.230 --> 28:08.753
How you conduct yourself, how you live your life to glorify Christ.

28:09.053 --> 28:09.934
That's the biggest thing.

28:09.954 --> 28:12.978
And I can tell people that because my focus is in the right place.

28:13.954 --> 28:20.327
There's a weekend in February, every single year where you will not find me here because I actually go to the state tournament now.

28:20.687 --> 28:25.437
There was a five-year gap from 2006 to 2011 where I couldn't go to Banker's Life Fieldhouse.

28:26.198 --> 28:27.822
Five years, I didn't go.

28:28.383 --> 28:31.369
I wouldn't take free Pacers tickets, I wouldn't take anything.

28:31.389 --> 28:32.571
But now I go back every year.

28:32.611 --> 28:36.018
Not only do I go, I'm the dork sitting mat side.

28:36.130 --> 28:41.276
that the state tournament with a microphone in my face, because I get to do play-by-play color commentary, the state tournament.

28:41.536 --> 28:42.938
It's an absolute blast.

28:42.958 --> 28:44.480
And by the end of it, I've got no voice.

28:45.061 --> 28:48.765
It's so much fun, and I'm just free to enjoy it because it's a blessing.

28:48.805 --> 28:51.688
It's something that God's given me because my focus is in the right place.

28:52.790 --> 29:03.282
The coolest thing about all of this, though, is that now, if we're at the house, and there happens to be a college dressing match on that I'm watching, I got a four-year-old daughter, and she just wants to be involved in anything Daddy's involved with.

29:03.458 --> 29:07.522
So she'll kind of like tattle into the room and she'll look at me and she'll say, Daddy, can I watch this with you?

29:09.324 --> 29:13.949
And now I get to take the same pause that Wyatt Earp did when he got off the train in Tombstone.

29:15.431 --> 29:19.976
And I can sit there with my daughter and I can just appreciate that moment and I can be grateful in that moment.

29:20.436 --> 29:24.521
For her, for wrestling, for everything, I can take that same pause that God did.

29:24.541 --> 29:31.769
After the sixth day of creation, when he looked out and we saw that everything he created was good and he could take that moment and pause and reflect and he could be grateful.

29:31.829 --> 29:33.170
I can take that same moment

29:33.346 --> 29:35.709
And I can take that same pause and I can look at her and I can say yes.

29:36.631 --> 29:38.453
We can watch this and we can enjoy this together.

29:39.475 --> 29:41.097
Because now my focus is in the right place.

29:41.478 --> 29:42.599
My heart's in the right place.

29:42.960 --> 29:44.642
I know that Jesus is my source of perfection.

29:44.662 --> 29:45.844
I don't have to chase that anymore.

29:46.985 --> 29:53.835
That's what having a right focus and a right attitude towards God and that's what having gratitude in your life can look like.

29:55.658 --> 29:58.502
So I want to ask you, what would this look like in your life?

29:59.904 --> 30:01.426
If you could stop the rush

30:01.666 --> 30:04.090
And if you could pause for just a little bit.

30:04.110 --> 30:11.061
If you could pause and you can make one day out of your week a day where you could receive everything, where you could engage and establish, what would that look like for you?

30:11.662 --> 30:28.690
If you could decide that you don't have to get your way and you could prefer your spouse and you could put other people first, whether it's a coworker, a stranger, a friend, a family member, man, what would that look like in your life if you could get your focus so fixated and so laser sharp on Jesus Christ and who He is and what He's done for you?

30:29.986 --> 30:40.619
Man, I'm telling you, if you can do that, and you could just slow it down a little bit, and you can get your gratitude right, you're gonna experience that sense of freedom like nothing the world can offer.

30:40.639 --> 30:43.984
And for some of you today, you're craving that sense of freedom.

30:44.645 --> 30:51.954
You feel locked up, you feel rushed, you feel busy, everything's gotta go your way, or your world falls apart, your focus is scattered, you're all over the place, you don't know what to do.

30:52.955 --> 30:58.482
But maybe you came today, and we're talking about Jesus and something's stirring, and maybe something's been stirring you for a while.

30:59.554 --> 31:01.076
or somebody at work invited you here.

31:02.117 --> 31:05.961
And you don't know what it is, but you're feeling some type of pull.

31:05.981 --> 31:22.139
Then you need to know that Jesus Christ, the one who came down and humbled himself enough to live right alongside you and me, that same Jesus, the same Jesus that lived a perfect, sinless life, gave his life for you on the cross as a perfect sacrifice.

31:23.181 --> 31:27.986
He died, he was crucified, he was mocked, he was beaten, and he did that.

31:28.738 --> 31:35.346
and he rose again three days later, conquering the penalty of sin and death so that you and I can have a relationship with God the Father.

31:36.428 --> 31:38.290
And some of you have not stepped into that.

31:38.310 --> 31:39.512
Some of you have not trusted that.

31:39.552 --> 31:46.160
Some of you have not chosen to be grateful for that, but maybe today is the day when you decide, I want to be grateful for that sacrifice.

31:46.200 --> 31:48.984
Today is the day, I'm ready.

31:49.084 --> 31:51.587
And if that's you, I want to walk you through that right now.

31:51.607 --> 31:52.889
I want to give you the chance to do that.

31:52.909 --> 31:53.609
So here's what you do.

31:54.410 --> 31:57.234
You just simply ask for forgiveness for your sins.

31:57.570 --> 32:03.097
You go to Jesus right now, you tell him I'm broken, I'm a sinner, I've messed up, but I want to turn away from all that junk.

32:03.117 --> 32:05.280
And man, I just want to follow you forever.

32:05.901 --> 32:07.403
I'm thankful for your sacrifice.

32:08.063 --> 32:09.545
I acknowledge that you died on a cross.

32:09.565 --> 32:11.308
I acknowledge that you rose again three days later.

32:12.409 --> 32:14.732
God help me.

32:14.752 --> 32:17.996
If you do that, you have a relationship with Christ.

32:18.016 --> 32:19.278
So I'm going to lead you a simple prayer.

32:19.939 --> 32:21.381
You take these words, make them your own.

32:21.961 --> 32:22.482
Let's pray.

32:27.298 --> 32:33.086
Jesus, I come to you today asking begging for your forgiveness.

32:36.151 --> 32:40.156
Jesus, I have made mistakes, but I want to turn away from my old life.

32:42.840 --> 32:44.683
Jesus, I've heard today that you died from me.

32:46.726 --> 32:47.947
I heard that you were crucified.

32:50.391 --> 32:55.538
I heard the amazing fact that you rose again three days later conquering this penalty of sin and death just for me.

32:57.474 --> 32:58.656
Jesus, I believe this.

33:00.118 --> 33:01.099
I want to live for you.

33:03.202 --> 33:06.407
I want to turn away, and I want to walk with you for the rest of my life.

33:08.290 --> 33:14.038
Jesus, show me what it means to be grateful for you every single day in my existence.

33:14.058 --> 33:14.739
Help me to be humble.

33:16.442 --> 33:19.506
And Jesus, it's in your name of Holy Pray, amen.

